<title>-MOVE-TOWARDS-ANOTHER</title>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Language" content="en-gb">
</head>
<body>
	<h3><i>I move horizontally or vertically towards the patch of another agent.</i> </h3>

	<font size="2" color="gray">Begin micro-behaviour</font>
	<p><b>MOVE-TOWARDS-ANOTHER</b></p>

	<font size="2" color="gray">Begin NetLogo code:</font>
	<pre>substitute-text-area-for columns: 77 expression-for-other the-other                             
substitute-text-area-for columns: 77 speed 1                                                   
          
move-horizontally-or-vertically-towards-another 
   expression-for-other <i>; other agent</i>
   speed <i>; maximum distance moved</i></pre>

	<font size="2" color="gray">End NetLogo code</font>
	<h2>Variants</h2>

	<p><i>the-other</i> is a variable referring to another individual. You can 

	replace it an expression such as <i>any-of-kind &quot;Prototype1&quot;</i>.&nbsp; 
	You can change the speed of the movement.</p>

	<h2>Related Micro-behaviours</h2>


	<p><a href="REPEATEDLY-MOVE-TOWARDS-ANOTHER.html">REPEATEDLY-MOVE-TOWARDS-ANOTHER</a> 
	<i>repeatedly</i> moves towards another.</p>
	<p><a title="MOVE-FORWARD" href="MOVE-FORWARD.html">MOVE-FORWARD</a> can be 
	used together with either:</p>
<blockquote>
	<p><a title="TURN-TOWARDS-GOAL" href="TURN-TOWARDS-GOAL.html">TURN-TOWARDS-GOAL</a> -- I turn towards a goal</p>
	<p><a title="TURN-TOWARDS-ANOTHER" href="TURN-TOWARDS-ANOTHER.html">TURN-TOWARDS-ANOTHER</a> -- I turn towards another individual</p>
</blockquote>
<p>

	to move towards a goal or another.</p>

	<h2>How this works</h2>

	<p>I use the move-horizontally-or-vertically-towards-another BehaviourComposer 
	command to move <i>speed</i> units towards the patch of 
	<b>
	<a target="_blank" href="http://resources.modelling4all.org/documents/programming-guide#toc2">the-other</a></b>.&nbsp; 
	The odds of whether it moves horizontally or vertically is proportional to 
	the horizontal and vertical distance to <b>the-other</b>.</p>

	<h2>History</h2>

	<p>This was implemented by Ken Kahn.</p>
</body>
